SIMPLE: once
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Once
<hw>Once</hw> <pr>(⟦ocr⟧ns)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>
<def>The ounce.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Once</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Once
<hw>Once</hw> <pr>(w⟦ucr⟧ns)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>ones</ets>, <ets>anes</ets>, an adverbial form fr. <ets>one</ets>,
<ets>on</ets>, <ets>an</ets>, one. See <er>One-</er>,
<er>-Wards</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>For one time; by limitation to
the number one; not twice nor any number of times more than
one.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye shall . . . go round about the city <qex>once</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Josh. vi. 3.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Trees that bear mast are fruitful but <qex>once</qex> in two
years.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>At some one period of time; -- used
indefinitely.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My soul had <qex>once</qex> some foolish fondness for thee.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That court which we shall <qex>once</qex> govern.</q> <rj><qau>Bp.
Hall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>At any one time; -- often nearly equivalent to
<sig>ever</sig>, <sig>if ever</sig>, or <sig>whenever</sig>; <as>as,
<ex>once</ex> kindled, it may not be quenched</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wilt thou not be made clean? When shall it <qex>once</qex> be?</q>
<rj><qau>Jer. xiii. 27.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To be <qex>once</qex> in doubt⟦br⟧
Is <qex>once</qex> to be resolved.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Once</xex> is used as a noun when preceded by
<xex>this</xex> or <xex>that</xex>; as, <xex>this once</xex>, <xex>that
once</xex>. It is also sometimes used elliptically, like an adjective,
for <xex>once-existing</xex>. ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>once</xex> province of
Britain.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>J. N. Pomeroy.</au></note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>At once</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>At the same point of
time; immediately; without delay.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Stand not upon the order
of your going, but go <xex>at once</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧I
. . . withdrew <xex>at once</xex> and altogether.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Jeffrey.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>At one and the same time;
simultaneously; in one body; <as>as, they all moved <ex>at
once</ex></as>.</cd> -- <col><b>Once and again</b></col>, <cd>once and
once more; repeatedly.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧A dove sent forth <xex>once and
again</xex>, to spy.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Milton.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>once-over</ent>⟦br⟧
